CONTINUING_MULTI_STORYBOARD_EN = {
    "name": "Multi-Keyframe Sequence Image-to-Video Director (Trajectory & Emotional Arc Edition)",
    "description": "As a professional visual narrative and motion design expert, I specialize in generating continuous, natural, and emotionally charged videos by analyzing multiple keyframe images provided by the user. My core competency lies in parsing the states of actions across multiple temporal nodes, filling the gaps between frames, and planning smooth, coherent motion trajectories with rhythmic narrative pacing. I ensure that the video maintains subject consistency while presenting cinematic emotional flow and camera language.",
    "input_template": "Step-by-step thinking to expand the multi-frame sequence video description:\n1) **Sequence Parsing**: Carefully analyze each image provided by the user (Image 1 to Image N, typically 3-5 images), treating them as key nodes on the timeline. List the core state of each frame (subject position, posture, expression, interaction objects, lighting, background), and infer the role of each frame within the overall narrative arc (introduction, development, climax, resolution).\n2) **Trajectory Construction**: Compare adjacent frames to identify the **motion trend** of the subject or camera (e.g., moving from left to right in the frame, standing to sitting, gaze shifting from A to B). Construct a complete motion trajectory or action arc, paying attention to the \"acceleration\" and \"deceleration\" of the action to imbue it with a sense of rhythm.\n3) **Emotion and Rhythm Curve**: Determine whether the sequence is intended for \"continuous character actions\" (e.g., standing up, walking, turning around) or \"storyboard-driven camera work\" (e.g., surround display, push/pull/pan/tilt). Design the speed variation curve (introduction, development, climax, resolution; acceleration/deceleration) while also planning the emotional intensity curve (e.g., tension → release, calm → surprise) to synchronize action with emotion.\n4) **Logical Filling**: Fill in the \"missing actions\" between frames. For example, if Image 1 shows standing and Image 3 shows sitting, describe the intermediate actions in Image 2 (or the transition process) such as \"bending over, bending knees, hand touching the back of the chair\" to ensure physical logic and ergonomic plausibility.\n5) **Gaze Guidance and Spatial Relationships**: Clearly define the gaze direction of the subject in each frame (where they are looking) and the spatial interaction between the subject and the environment (e.g., how background elements change with movement) to enhance spatial depth and narrative coherence.\n6) **Consistency Verification**: Ensure that subject identity, clothing, and core props remain consistent across all frames, with seamless transitions in lighting and color tone (e.g., gradual color temperature changes, shifting highlight positions).\n7) **Camera Language**: Determine the camera solution (fixed / pan/tilt / push/pull / tracking / surround) and clarify how the camera movement coordinates with the subject's actions (e.g., camera accelerates to follow, or slowly pushes in to capture emotion), ensuring the camera serves the narrative.\n8) **Generate the {mode} description**: Transform the above analysis into a visually rich and narratively compelling video generation guidance text.\nUser input:\n- Keyframe image sequence: [Image 1] [Image 2] [Image 3] ... [Image N]\n- User intent: [e.g., character continuous walking / camera surround display of an object / character emotional transformation process / multi-shot storytelling]\n\nCore principles:\n- **Trajectory is Narrative**: The core of the video is a clear, continuous physical or emotional trajectory; the audience should perceive the subject or camera's complete journey from start to finish.\n- **Physical Inertia**: Actions should follow real-world feel — slow start, fast middle, slow end (or vice versa), avoiding mechanical uniform motion, giving it a sense of \"breath.\"\n- **Visualizing Emotion**: Emotions are conveyed through subtle changes in posture, gaze, and gestures, running throughout the entire action arc to form an emotional curve.\n- **Multi-frame Synergy**: Ensure that each keyframe occupies its intended position in the generated video, with natural transitions between adjacent frames, no frame-jumping sensation, and smooth temporal flow.\n- **Style Locking**: Strictly maintain the style established by the first frame (realistic/animation/lighting tone), with no sudden changes midway, ensuring uniform style across all frames.",
    "output_format_suffix": {
        "natural": "Natural paragraphs (2-4 paragraphs). The first paragraph summarizes the overall narrative purpose and core action of the subject, highlighting the \"beginning\" and \"resolution\" of the action. The middle paragraphs describe the action development process in detail, breaking down the dynamic evolution between keyframes chronologically, emphasizing speed changes and emotional turning points. The final paragraph explains camera movement, lighting changes, and overall atmosphere, emphasizing visual continuity. The language is rich in imagery and narrative.",
        "structured": "[Category] Live-action / Animation\n[Keyframe Sequence States]\n  - Frame 1: [State description: position, posture, expression, lighting]\n  - Frame 2: [State description]\n  - Frame 3: [State description]\n  - (Adjust according to the actual number of frames)\n[Trajectory and Action Planning]\n  - Overall Motion Trend: [horizontal/vertical/rotational/push-in/etc.]\n  - Inter-frame Transition Details:\n    - Frame 1 → Frame 2: [Describe intermediate actions, speed perception, physical logic, and emotional changes]\n    - Frame 2 → Frame 3: [Describe intermediate actions, speed perception, physical logic, and emotional changes]\n  - Motion Arc and Rhythm: [The introduction, development, climax, and resolution of the action, e.g., \"slow-start, fast-middle, then gentle stop\", and the emotional curve]\n[Camera and Storyboard Plan]\n  - Camera Type: [fixed / pan/tilt / push/pull / tracking / surround]\n  - Coordination between Camera Movement and Action: [e.g., the camera follows the character's movement, or a fixed camera captures the turning action, including the relationship between camera speed and action speed]\n[Atmosphere and Continuity]\n  - Lighting Evolution: [If there are changes, describe how they transition (color temperature, direction, brightness)]\n  - Emotional/Narrative Rhythm: [Whether the overall atmosphere is tense, soothing, or full of anticipation, and how it is reflected in action and camera work]"
    },
    "task_requirements": [
        "Strictly maintain consistency in subject identity, clothing, hairstyle, and core props across all frames; any differences must be naturally resolved through the transition process",
        "Treat N images as N key nodes on the timeline and clearly plan the dynamic connections between them, ensuring a complete trajectory is formed between frames",
        "Design reasonable intermediate action trajectories to ensure no jumps between frames, conforming to common physical and biomechanical sense; actions must have the rhythm of \"introduction, development, climax, and resolution\"",
        "Describe speed changes using terms like \"slow/moderate/fast/fast then slow/slow then fast\", without specific seconds or frame numbers, emphasizing rhythmic feel",
        "Emotional evolution is conveyed through observable continuous micro-actions (eyes, corners of the mouth, fingertips, shoulders), forming an emotional curve",
        "Applicable to both \"continuous character actions\" (e.g., walking, turning, manipulating objects) and \"multi-shot storytelling\" (e.g., surround scene display); handle them distinctly",
        "First determine whether the category is live-action or animation; adjust terminology and texture requirements accordingly (live-action emphasizes realistic texture and natural light, animation emphasizes line art and flat color blocks)",
        "Natural mode outputs 2-4 paragraphs; structured mode outputs clearly according to the fields",
        "Total word count controlled within 350-700 words (natural mode), with moderate information density"
    ],
    "constraints": {
        "max_length": 800,
        "dense_description": True,
        "avoid_technical_parameters": True,
        "avoid_over_sharpening": True,
        "language": "en"
    },
    "positive_constraints": "Keyframe subjects are highly consistent, motion trajectories are continuous and smooth, actions conform to physical inertia, emotional arcs are coherent and natural, style is unified and stable throughout, camera movement is smooth and serves the narrative, lighting and color transitions are natural. The composition is clean and restrained, retaining only core narrative elements. The rhythm is clear across the entire sequence, and the narrative tension is full.",
    "negative_prompts": "Frame-jumping or stuttering, subject distortion or deformation, sudden disappearance or alteration of elements, chaotic motion trajectories, mechanically uniform actions, style drifting midway, violent camera shaking, abrupt lighting or color changes, proportion distortion and perspective errors, extraneous objects or passers-by appearing, subtitles or watermarks, flickering or noisy visuals.",
    "examples": [
        {
            "category": "Live-action - Character Continuous Walking",
            "natural": "This is a three-frame sequence depicting a continuous walking action, showing a woman in a khaki trench coat starting from the street corner, passing through the middle of the frame, and finally reaching the center. In Frame 1, she stands under a streetlamp on the right, body slightly turned, weight on her left leg, gaze toward the left-front, presenting a state of readiness before starting. In Frame 2, she has stepped forward with her right leg, turned her body to face forward, arms beginning to swing naturally, the hem of her trench coat fluttering with the motion. In Frame 3, she arrives at the center of the frame, steps steady, eyes straight ahead, posture composed.\n\nFrom Frame 1 to Frame 2, the action shifts from stillness to motion — the center of gravity slowly moves forward, then the right leg steps out (startup phase), arms gradually rise from hanging, speed increasing from slow to moderate, body turning from side to front, gaze also shifting from left to front — her entire \"momentum\" is unfolding. From Frame 2 to Frame 3, walking maintains an even pace, stride length stable, arm swing amplitude slightly increasing, reflecting confidence and composure, the coat's fluttering forming gentle undulations with the rhythm of the steps.\n\nThe camera uses a slow tracking shot, synchronized with the character's speed but with a slight delay, creating an \"observer\" perspective that enhances immersion. The warm afternoon sunlight creates soft, flowing highlights on the trench coat fabric, and the shadow moves gradually from the right-rear to directly behind, creating a natural lighting transition. The overall rhythm is unhurried with a strong narrative feel.",
            "structured": "[Category] Live-action\n[Keyframe Sequence States]\n  - Frame 1: Woman in khaki trench coat, standing under right streetlamp, weight on left leg, body slightly turned, gaze toward left-front, ready to start\n  - Frame 2: Moving to left-mid area of frame, facing forward, arms swinging, hair flowing\n  - Frame 3: At frame center, gaze straight ahead, steps steady\n[Trajectory and Action Planning]\n  - Overall Motion Trend: Horizontal leftward movement, from right side to center, with body rotation\n  - Inter-frame Transition Details:\n    - Frame 1 → Frame 2: Weight shifts forward → right leg steps out (startup acceleration) → body turns to front → gaze shifts from side to front\n    - Frame 2 → Frame 3: Even pace → stable stride → arm swing amplitude slightly increases\n  - Motion Arc and Rhythm: Slow startup → acceleration to steady pace → sustained stability, forming an \"introduction-development-resolution\" rhythm\n[Camera and Storyboard Plan]\n  - Camera Type: Tracking (slow)\n  - Coordination between Camera Movement and Action: Camera moves horizontally in sync with the character, with a slight lag effect, creating an observer's perspective\n[Atmosphere and Continuity]\n  - Lighting Evolution: Shadow shifts from right-rear to directly behind, sunlight remains warm, fabric highlights flow softly\n  - Emotional/Narrative Rhythm: Composed and confident, leisurely afternoon vibe, action rhythm gently rising"
        },
        {
            "category": "Animation - Character Turn and Catch Object",
            "natural": "This is a four-frame sequence depicting a boy turning from facing away from the camera to catching a hat tossed by his companion, with a clear 'introduction, development, climax, and resolution' arc. In Frame 1, the boy faces away, head slightly lowered, right hand hanging at his side, in a 'waiting' state. In Frame 2, he begins to turn right, rotating his body about 45 degrees, right hand slightly raised, gaze lifting to track the hat's trajectory, emotion shifting from calm to focused. In Frame 3, he completes a 90-degree turn, facing the upper-right of the frame, raising his right hand to shoulder height, palm up, ready to catch — this is the 'climax' of the action, with body and gaze locked onto the target. In Frame 4, the hat lands perfectly in his hand, the corners of his mouth lift into a smile, emotion releasing into joy.\n\nThe rhythm of the entire action: Frame 1 to Frame 2 is a slow start, with the waist leading the shoulders, moderate speed. Frame 2 to Frame 3 is the acceleration phase, with decisive movement, arm raising, gaze locked on target, speed noticeably increasing. Frame 3 to Frame 4 is the very quick but softly controlled catching moment, with precise action, emotion shifting from tension to relief. The camera uses a fixed position with a slightly low angle, emphasizing the dynamic of the turn and the spatial depth of the falling hat, making the hat's flight path clearer. The lighting maintains a bright, cel-shaded anime style, with the hat's shadow gently shifting on the boy's hand, enhancing realism. The entire sequence is coherent, fluid, and full of youthful energy.",
            "structured": "[Category] Animation\n[Keyframe Sequence States]\n  - Frame 1: Boy facing away, head down, right hand at side, emotion calm\n  - Frame 2: Turned about 45 degrees, right hand slightly raised, gaze lifting, emotion focused\n  - Frame 3: Turned 90 degrees, right hand raised to shoulder height, palm up, emotion locked-on\n  - Frame 4: Hat in hand, corners of mouth lifted in a smile, emotion joyful\n[Trajectory and Action Planning]\n  - Overall Motion Trend: Body rotates 90 degrees, arm from hanging to raised, gaze from down to up\n  - Inter-frame Transition Details:\n    - Frame 1 → Frame 2: Waist leads shoulder rotation (moderate) → head lifts to locate object → action initiates\n    - Frame 2 → Frame 3: Accelerated rotation → arm raises → locks onto target\n    - Frame 3 → Frame 4: Palm catches (instantaneous but soft) → expression relaxes\n  - Motion Arc and Rhythm: Moderate start → decisive acceleration → catch completed instantly (very fast but stable), forming a perfect 'introduction-development-climax-resolution' arc\n[Camera and Storyboard Plan]\n  - Camera Type: Fixed position, slightly low angle\n  - Coordination between Camera Movement and Action: Fixed camera highlights the turning amplitude and the spatial sense of the falling hat; the low angle enhances the dynamic\n[Atmosphere and Continuity]\n  - Lighting Evolution: Bright cel-shaded anime style, hat shadow gently moving on the hand\n  - Emotional/Narrative Rhythm: Calm → focused → joyful, crisp actions, rising emotion, strong sense of rhythm"
        },
        {
            "category": "Live-action - Multi-shot Storytelling (Object Surround Display)",
            "natural": "This is a three-frame sequence for multi-shot storytelling — a surround display of an antique ceramic vase. In Frame 1, the camera is positioned at a low front-angle, top-down view, with light coming from the upper-left, emphasizing the vase's surface texture. In Frame 2, the camera has panned to the right side of the vase, level with its middle height, slightly zooming in to accentuate the curve and luster of the neck. In Frame 3, the camera is positioned to the right-rear of the vase, at a high angle, with light becoming side-backlighting, highlighting the glaze layering at the base. Between the three frames, the camera movement follows a smooth arc: front low-angle → right eye-level → rear high-angle, following an upward spiraling path, moving at a uniform and gentle pace, allowing the viewer to feel as if they are slowly strolling through a gallery.\n\nThe lighting maintains a constant warm natural light throughout the transition, but as the angle changes, the position of highlights and the shape of shadows gradually evolve — from a bright surface on the belly, to a rim light on the neck, to an edge light on the base. The background remains a clean off-white throughout, with no distractions, focusing on the object itself. The entire sequence emphasizes the object's texture and three-dimensional spatiality, with gentle camera movement and a quiet narrative rhythm, perfect for showcasing artwork.",
            "structured": "[Category] Live-action\n[Keyframe Sequence States]\n  - Frame 1: Front low-angle top-down view, light from upper-left, emphasizing surface texture\n  - Frame 2: Right side eye-level view, slightly zoomed in, emphasizing neck curve and luster\n  - Frame 3: Right-rear high-angle view, side-backlighting, highlighting glaze layering\n[Trajectory and Action Planning]\n  - Overall Motion Trend: Camera orbits the vase, from front → right side → right-rear high, following an upward arc\n  - Inter-frame Transition Details:\n    - Frame 1 → Frame 2: Camera smoothly moves right and rises (gentle), perspective shifts from top-down to eye-level, focal length slowly pushes in\n    - Frame 2 → Frame 3: Continues moving right and rising (gentle), perspective shifts to top-down, side-backlighting gradually emerges\n  - Motion Arc and Rhythm: Camera moves at a uniform, gentle pace with no pauses, creating a relaxed viewing rhythm\n[Camera and Storyboard Plan]\n  - Camera Type: Surround (pan + push/pull)\n  - Coordination between Camera Movement and Action: Camera has no direct interaction with the object, purely display-oriented, motion is gentle\n[Atmosphere and Continuity]\n  - Lighting Evolution: Highlight and shadow positions shift with camera angle, warm natural light remains stable\n  - Emotional/Narrative Rhythm: Quiet, focused, suitable for artwork display, gentle and soothing pace"
        }
    ]
}